From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Jun 2026 14:00:19 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] targets: running-only view via per-edge run-state from the
 build executor
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The targets (build_edges) pane now shows only the targets CURRENTLY building
on a live box (default), so a hung build's in-flight edge is obvious — matching
the procs and pipelines running-only behavior. Each edge also carries its wall
time and exit code.

The build_edges table already had started_ts / ended_ts / exit_code columns
("filled in BY THE BUILDER as edges run") but nothing filled them. Both
in-process build engines now report each recipe's run-state as it enters and
leaves the executor:

- kati: a new `EdgeReporter` hook in fileutil.rs (mirroring `RECIPE_RUNNER`, so
  kati stays decoupled from sarun) is called from `run_node_commands` around
  each node's recipe — keyed by the node's primary output (== outs[0]).
  Command-less / dry-run nodes (phony, up-to-date) are left un-started.
- n2: `n2_executor` reports around `run_recipe_in_process`, keyed by the exact
  cmdline (== the stored build_edges.cmd). Phony / up-to-date edges never reach
  the executor, so they stay un-started.

Both ship a `build_edge_state` control message (same broker path as the
per-pipeline provenance) carrying its own pidfd; the engine resolves the box
and stamps the matching build_edges row (`mark_build_edge_started` /
`mark_build_edge_done`, matched by output via json_extract or by cmd). The
live box writes the same .sqlar discover reads, so marks are visible live.

UI: `edges_running_only` (default true, gated on a live box — a finished box
shows all, where "running" is meaningless), `f` toggles it on the Targets pane.
The row renderer and detail show a running marker, wall time, and exit (red on
failure). The pane refreshes on `build_edges` events so it tracks a live build.

Verified end to end: a make build and a ninja build each mark their real
recipes started/ended with wall time + exit 0 and leave phony/up-to-date edges
un-started; json_extract works in the bundled SQLite. kati corpus parity
unchanged (365/379, fail=0); 107 engine unit tests pass (incl. a new
edge_running predicate test); make test passes.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01XyA6FzC6QGgsrjEYEBJV46
---
 src-rs/exec.rs     | 18 +++++++++++++++++-
 src-rs/fileutil.rs | 37 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 2 files changed, 54 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src-rs/exec.rs b/src-rs/exec.rs
index 7ce9f12..36a85f8 100644
--- a/src-rs/exec.rs
+++ b/src-rs/exec.rs
@@ -279,6 +279,17 @@ fn run_node_commands(
     let mut prefix = req.box_prefix.to_vec();
     prefix.extend_from_slice(&exports_prefix(&req.exports));
     let cwd = req.cwd;
+    // sarun: report this edge's run-state to the engine so the targets pane can
+    // show only the targets currently building (and their wall time). Only edges
+    // that actually run a recipe are reported — dry-run and command-less (phony /
+    // up-to-date) nodes are correctly left un-started. `req.output` is the node's
+    // primary output (== build_edges.outs[0], the engine's match key).
+    let output = req.output;
+    let report = !FLAGS.is_dry_run && !req.commands.is_empty();
+    if report {
+        crate::fileutil::report_edge(output.as_bytes().as_ref(),
+                                     crate::fileutil::EdgePhase::Start, 0);
+    }
     for command in req.commands {
         if command.echo {
             // Echo LIVE, before running, so a hung command's line shows at once.
@@ -319,7 +330,12 @@ fn run_node_commands(
             }
         }
     }
-    NodeRun { output: req.output, ignored, failure, result_ts: req.result_ts }
+    if report {
+        let code = failure.map(|(_, c)| c).unwrap_or(0);
+        crate::fileutil::report_edge(output.as_bytes().as_ref(),
+                                     crate::fileutil::EdgePhase::Done, code);
+    }
+    NodeRun { output, ignored, failure, result_ts: req.result_ts }
 }
 
 impl<'a> Executor<'a> {
diff --git a/src-rs/fileutil.rs b/src-rs/fileutil.rs
index f4ba39f..a9e2d43 100644
--- a/src-rs/fileutil.rs
+++ b/src-rs/fileutil.rs
@@ -102,6 +102,43 @@ pub fn run_with_installed_runner(
         RecipeRunnerDecision::Passthrough => None,
     }
 }
+
+// sarun: optional hook reporting a node's recipe run-state transitions so the
+// embedding engine can stamp the box's `build_edges` row (started_ts /
+// ended_ts + exit_code) and the UI can show only the targets CURRENTLY
+// building (and each target's wall time). Decoupled exactly like RECIPE_RUNNER:
+// kati calls `report_edge` around each node's recipe; sarun installs a closure
+// that ships the transition to the engine. No-op (rkati standalone) when none
+// is installed. `output` is the node's primary output name (== the first entry
+// of the build_edges row's `outs` array, the engine's match key).
+#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
+pub enum EdgePhase {
+    /// Recipe is about to run (its first concrete command is starting).
+    Start,
+    /// Recipe finished; `code` is the exit status (0 = success).
+    Done,
+}
+
+pub type EdgeReporter =
+    Arc<dyn Fn(&[u8] /* output */, EdgePhase, i32 /* exit code */) + Send + Sync + 'static>;
+
+static EDGE_REPORTER: parking_lot::Mutex<Option<EdgeReporter>> =
+    parking_lot::Mutex::new(None);
+
+/// Install the build-edge run-state reporter. Idempotent; last call wins.
+pub fn install_edge_reporter(f: EdgeReporter) {
+    *EDGE_REPORTER.lock() = Some(f);
+}
+
+/// Report a build edge run-state transition through the installed reporter, if
+/// any. Best-effort: no reporter → no-op. The reporter Arc is cloned and the
+/// lock released before the call (the reporter may do I/O / re-enter kati).
+pub fn report_edge(output: &[u8], phase: EdgePhase, code: i32) {
+    let r = EDGE_REPORTER.lock().clone();
+    if let Some(r) = r {
+        r(output, phase, code);
+    }
+}
 use parking_lot::Mutex;
 
 use crate::log;
